			System.out.println("OK");
		else
			if (args.length < 3)
				System.out.println("KO");
	}

public static void main(String[] args) {
		args = new String[6];
		if (args.length <= 5) //(1)
			if (args.length < 3) // (2)
				System.out.println("KO");
		else
			System.out.println("OK"); // goes with if at (1)
	}

public static void main(String[] args) {
		args = new String[6];
		if (args.length <= 5) //(1)
			if (args.length < 3) // (2)
				System.out.println("KO");
		else
		  System.out.println("OK"); //goes with if at <b>(2)</b> 
	}

Bug.WithStack:
"Inverse if statement" quick assist replaces

		if (args.length > 5)
			System.out.println("OK");
		else
			if (args.length < 3)
				System.out.println("KO");

with

		if (args.length <= 5)
			if (args.length < 3)
				System.out.println("KO");
		else
			System.out.println("OK");
That looks fine to me. What would you expect?
if (args.length <= 5) {
	if (args.length < 3)
		System.out.println("KO");
} else
	System.out.println("OK");
That's the same, brackets are not required there.

'if (args.length < 3)
   System.out.println("KO");'

is one statement.

Note that you can use quick assist on the 'if' to add brackets if you like.
For me, it's not the same at all.
When I execute 

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		args = new String[6];
		if (args.length > 5)
			System.out.println("OK");
		else
			if (args.length < 3)
				System.out.println("KO");
	}

OK in written in the console.
After the quick fix execution :

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		args = new String[6];
		if (args.length <= 5) //(1)
			if (args.length < 3) // (2)
				System.out.println("KO");
		else
			System.out.println("OK"); // goes with if at (1)
	}

nothing is written because "else System.out.println("OK")" goes with "if
(args.length < 3) " instead of "if (args.length <= 5)"

As seen in the Java Language Specification 14.5:

"The Java programming language, like C and C++ and many programming languages
before them, arbitrarily decree that an else clause belongs to the innermost if
to which it might possibly belong"

http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/second_edition/html/statements.doc.html#5958
 
The comments shoud be amended to read :

After the quick fix execution :
 	public static void main(String[] args) {
		args = new String[6];
		if (args.length <= 5) //(1)
			if (args.length < 3) // (2)
				System.out.println("KO");
		else
		  System.out.println("OK"); //goes with if at <b>(2)</b> 
	}

fixed > 20050519

Thanks for your help!
