Bug.WithOutStack:
Display.getShells() and Disply.getActiveShell() methods are called in eclipse 
very frequently. For example during opening of 40 Java editors Display.getShells
() was called about 12 000 times and this method took 2.2% of total scenario 
execution time.

This is due to widgetTable, which contains hundreds of widgets, is scanned each 
time. However amount of non-disposed shells is about 2-4 depending on amount of 
opened dialogs. So it is better to keep separate array of non-disposed shells 
rather than scan throw widgetTable.

In next post I am going to attach this patch.
Created attachment 16169
Display & Shell patch
Newer version of GTK have API to query the active shell.  FH to investigate to 
see whether we can reduce the number of calls to getShells().
There is no OS call to obtain the active Shell, the call you were thinking of is
gtk_window_list_toplevel ().  This call returns every top level window on GTK
and it is slower than going through the list in Java.

I have optimized getActiveShell() not to call getShells().  We don't really want
to make a special case of Shells in the widget table.  Artyom, can you rerun
your benchmark?  Specifically, why is getShells() called so many times from Eclipse?
New version of Display.getActiveShell() is 4.5 times faster. Thanks for fixing 
this.

While we are here could you please also change Display.getShells() method 
something like this.

public Shell [] getShells () {
  checkDevice ();
  final int shellGrow = 10; 
  Shell []shells = new Shell[shellGrow];
  int length = 0;

  main:
  for (int i=0; i<widgetTable.length; i++) {
    Widget widget = widgetTable [i];
    if (widget != null && widget instanceof Shell) {
      for(int j=0; j<length; j++)
        if(widget == shells[j]) continue main;
      if(length == shells.length) {
        Shell [] new_shells = new Shell[length + shellGrow];
        System.arraycopy(shells,0,new_shells,0,length);
        shells = new_shells;
      }
      shells[length++] = (Shell)widget;
    }
  }

  if (length == shells.length) return shells;
  Shell [] result = new Shell [length];
  System.arraycopy (shells, 0, result, 0, length);
  return result;
}

